The Pope, however, compelled him to apply himself asresh to his task of missionary preaching. On arriving at Maises on the Adige he incurred the wrath of Duke Grimoald by his boldness in rebuking him sor his marriage with Piltrud, the widow of his deceased brother3 and the persecution of Piltrud, rather than of Grimoald perhaps, forced him to flee to the Tyrol, whence he returned after the death of Grimoald in 724

He now founded the Monastery of Freising, on the Isar, in Bavaria, and dedicated it to the Blessed Virgin and to St. Benedict; it was raised to an episcopal seat, and Corbinian was himself the first Bishop.

He died on the 8th of September, 730 A.D., and was succeeded by his own brother Erimbert. Erimbert was succeeded by Arib0, who transferred the body os Corbinian back to F reising from Maises, whither‚ in accordance with his dying request, it had been conveyed. To Aribo also we are indcbted for a lise os the Saint and founder of the Monastery¹.
